\begin_layout Abstract
In analogy with the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we try to construct an analogous inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of differential operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, and are led to the concept of a Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 [the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{A}^{-1})_{\vec{x},\vec{x}'}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

matrix element
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

].
 Although 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a perfectly well-defined function, in trying to construct it and define
 its properties we are drawn inexorably to something that appears less well
 defined: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}G$
\end_inset

 seems to be some kind of function that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinitely concentrated at a point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

delta function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

