\begin_layout Subsection
Inverses in other bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is not the only way to write down 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

, of course, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are only one possible choice of basis.
 For example, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}_{1},\ldots,\vec{q}_{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 orthonormal basis for our vector space, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}_{j}$
\end_inset

 solves 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{u}_{j}=\vec{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write any 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}=\sum_{j}\vec{q}_{j}(\vec{q}_{j}^{*}\vec{f})$
\end_inset

 and hence the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{u}=\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}=A^{-1}\vec{f}=\sum_{j}\vec{u}_{j}(\vec{q}_{j}^{*}\vec{f})$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we are writing 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=\sum_{j}\vec{u}_{j}\vec{q}_{j}^{*}=\sum_{j}(A^{-1}\vec{q}_{j})\vec{q}_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 in terms of this basis.
 In matrix form, if 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is the (unitary) matrix whose columns are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

, then we are simply writing 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=(A^{-1}Q)Q^{*}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $QQ^{*}=I$
\end_inset

.
 [Similarly, if the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are any basis, not necessarily orthonormal, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=(A^{-1}B)B^{-1}$
\end_inset

: we solve any right-hand-side 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{f}$
\end_inset

 by a superposition of the solutions for the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{-1}\vec{f}$
\end_inset

.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian (
\begin_inset Formula $A=A^{*}$
\end_inset

), then we can choose the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

 to be orthonormal eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{q}_{j}=\lambda_{j}\vec{q}_{j}$
\end_inset

), in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}_{j}=\vec{q}_{j}/\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}=A^{-1}\vec{f}=\sum_{j}\vec{u}_{j}(\vec{q}_{j}^{*}\vec{f})=\sum_{j}\vec{q}_{j}(\vec{q}_{j}^{*}\vec{f})/\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 But this is just writing 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=Q\Lambda^{-1}Q^{*}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the (hopefully) familiar diagonalization 
\begin_inset Formula $A=Q\Lambda Q^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Operator inverses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we would like to consider the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, if such a thing exists.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\hat{A})=\{0\}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=f$
\end_inset

 has a unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in some suitable space of functions).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is then 
\series bold
whatever operator gives the solution
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\hat{A}^{-1}f$
\end_inset

 from any 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 This must clearly be a 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 operator, since if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u_{1}=f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u_{2}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\alpha u_{1}+\beta u_{2}$
\end_inset

 solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\alpha f_{1}+\beta f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, we already know how to write down 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, for self-adjoint 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, in terms of an orthonormal basis of eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}f=\sum_{n}u_{n}\langle u_{n},f\rangle/\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But now we would like to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 in a different way: analogous to the entries 
\begin_inset Formula $(A^{-1})_{ij}$
\end_inset

 above, we would like to write the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 as a superposition of 
\series bold
effects at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 from sources at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset


\series default
 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 just means another point, not a derivative): 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\boxed{u(\vec{x})=\hat{A}^{-1}f=\int_{\Omega}d^{d}\vec{x}'G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')f(\vec{x}')},\label{eq:G}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Green's function
\series default
 or the 
\series bold
fundamental solution
\series default
 to the PDE.
 We need to figure out what 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is (and whether it exists at all), and how to solve for it.
 This equation is the direct analogue of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=\sum_{j}(A^{-1})_{i,j}f_{j}$
\end_inset

 for the matrix case above, with sums turned into integrals, so this leads
 us to interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

matrix element
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{A}^{-1})_{\vec{x},\vec{x}'}$
\end_inset

.
 So, in analogy to the matrix case, we hope that 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
is the
\series default
 
\series bold
effect at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 from a source 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

.

\series default
 But what does this mean for a PDE?
\end_layout

